ans2)
methods of string
-----------------
1.search() : The search() method searches a string for a specified value and returns the position of the match.
 e.g.
    var str = "Please locate where 'locate' occurs!";
    var pos = str.search("locate");

2.slice() : slice() extracts a part of a string and returns the extracted part in a new string.
 e.g.
    var str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
    var res = str.slice(7, 13); //Banana
    var res = str.slice(7); //Banana, Kiwi
    var res = str.slice(-12); //Banana, Kiwi

3.substring() : substring() is similar to slice().The difference is that substring() cannot accept negative indexes.
 e.g.
    var str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
    var res = str.substring(7, 13); //Banana, Kiwi

4.substr() : substr() is similar to slice(). The difference is that the second parameter specifies the length of the extracted part.
 e.g.
    var str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
    var res = str.substr(7, 6);//Banana
    var res = str.substr(-4); //kiwi

5.replace() : The replace() method replaces a specified value with another value in a string.
 e.g.
    str = "Please visit Microsoft!";
    var n = str.replace("Microsoft", "Opera");

6.String.trim() : The trim() method removes whitespace from both sides of a string.
 e.g. 
    var str = "       Hello World!        ";
    alert(str.trim());

7.charAt() : The charAt() method returns the character at a specified index (position) in a string.
 e.g.
    var str = "HELLO WORLD";
    str.charAt(0); //H

8.charCodeAt() : The charCodeAt() method returns the unicode of the character at a specified index in a string.
 e.g.
    var str = "HELLO WORLD";
    str.charCodeAt(0);//72


Methods of Array
----------------

1.toString() : The JavaScript method toString() converts an array to a string.
 e.g.
    <p id="demo"></p>
    <script>
        var fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = fruits.toString();
    </script>

2.join() : The join() method also joins all array elements into a string.
    e.g.
        <p id="demo"></p>
        <script>
            var fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
            document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = fruits.join(" * ");
        </script>

3.pop() : The pop() method removes the last element from an array.
 e.g.
    var fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
    fruits.pop(); 

4.push() : The push() method adds a new element to an array (at the end).
 e.g.
    var fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
    fruits.push("Kiwi");

5.delete : elements can be deleted by using the JavaScript operator delete.
 e.g. 
    var fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
    delete fruits[0];    

6.Splice() : The splice() method can be used to add new items to an array
 e.g. 
    var fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
    fruits.splice(2, 2, "Lemon", "Kiwi"); //Banana,Orange,Lemon,Kiwi

